Here's a simple function that takes a reference to a std::string containing markdown formatted text and returns a std::string containing html formatted text. It uses the MarkdownSharp library to convert the markdown to html.

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <markdownsharp.h>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    MarkdownSharp::MarkdownConverter converter;
    converter.Convert(markdown, html);
    return html;
}
```

You can use this function like this:

```cpp
std::string markdown = "This is some **markdown** text.";
std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
```

The function will return the html formatted text:

```html
This is some <strong>markdown</strong> text.
```

Note that you need to include the MarkdownSharp library in your project to use this function. You can download the library from the official website: https://github.com/toner/markdownsharp
